====================================================================
GKE + ASM (ISTIO) TRAFFIC FLOW & DEBUG RUNBOOK
====================================================================

PURPOSE
-------
Single reference document for understanding and debugging traffic
in Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) with in-cluster Anthos Service Mesh
(ASM / Istio).

This covers:
- Internal traffic (Pod → Pod)
- External traffic (Internet → App)
- Outbound traffic (Pod → Internet)
- All critical debug commands used in production.


====================================================================
1. HIGH LEVEL ARCHITECTURE
====================================================================

External (North-South):

[ Internet ]
     |
     v
[GCP Load Balancer]
     |
     v
[Istio Ingress Gateway (Envoy)]
     |
     v
[Kubernetes Service]
     |
     v
[Envoy Sidecar]
     |
     v
[Application Pod]

Internal (East-West):

Pod A → Envoy A → mTLS → Envoy B → Pod B


====================================================================
2. TRAFFIC TYPES
====================================================================

Type                Direction       Controlled By
-------------------------------------------------
Pod → Pod           East-West        Istio (Envoy)
Internet → App      North-South      GKE LB + Istio
Pod → Internet      Egress           Istio (optional)


====================================================================
3. KEY COMPONENTS
====================================================================

GKE Load Balancer:
- Provides public IP
- Health checks
- No routing logic

Istio Ingress Gateway:
- Envoy proxy
- Applies:
  - Host/path routing
  - TLS
  - Authentication
  - Canary/blue-green

VirtualService:
- Actual routing rules

DestinationRule:
- Version selection
- mTLS behavior

PeerAuthentication:
- mTLS mode:
  STRICT / PERMISSIVE / DISABLE


====================================================================
4. INTERNAL TRAFFIC FLOW (POD TO POD)
====================================================================

Pod A
 → iptables redirect
 → Envoy sidecar
 → mTLS
 → Envoy sidecar
 → Pod B

Notes:
- kube-proxy is bypassed
- Envoy controls everything
- Kubernetes Service only provides DNS


====================================================================
5. INGRESS FLOW (EXTERNAL TO APP)
====================================================================

User → DNS → GKE LB IP
 → istio-ingressgateway Service
 → Gateway
 → VirtualService
 → DestinationRule
 → Pod


====================================================================
6. EGRESS FLOW (OUTBOUND)
====================================================================

Default:
Pod → Envoy → Node NAT → Internet

With control:
Pod → Envoy → Egress Gateway → Internet

If outbound is restricted:
meshConfig:
  outboundTrafficPolicy:
    mode: REGISTRY_ONLY

Requires:
- ServiceEntry
- Optional EgressGateway


====================================================================
7. INGRESS DEBUG COMMANDS
====================================================================

Check LoadBalancer:
kubectl get svc -n istio-system

Check Gateway:
kubectl get gateway -A

Check VirtualServices:
kubectl get virtualservice -A

Check which VS uses which Gateway:
kubectl get virtualservice -A -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.namespace}{"\t"}{.metadata.name}{"\t"}{.spec.gateways}{"\n"}{end}'

Check ingress pod:
kubectl get pods -n istio-system
kubectl describe pod <gateway-pod>


====================================================================
8. ROUTING DEBUG
====================================================================

View routes inside Envoy:
istioctl proxy-config routes <gateway-pod> -n istio-system

View clusters (services):
istioctl proxy-config clusters <pod>


====================================================================
9. INTERNAL TRAFFIC DEBUG
====================================================================

Check sidecar injection:
kubectl get pod <pod> -o jsonpath='{.spec.containers[*].name}'

Must include:
istio-proxy

Check mTLS:
kubectl get peerauthentication -A
kubectl get destinationrule -A

View listeners:
istioctl proxy-config listeners <pod>

View endpoints:
istioctl proxy-config endpoints <pod>


====================================================================
10. GOLDEN TROUBLESHOOTING COMMANDS
====================================================================

These solve 80% of production issues:

kubectl get svc -n istio-system
kubectl get gateway -A
kubectl get virtualservice -A
kubectl get peerauthentication -A
istioctl proxy-status


====================================================================
11. COMMON FAILURE PATTERNS
====================================================================

Symptom                         Root Cause
--------------------------------------------------
404 from ingress                VS not bound to Gateway
External works, internal fails  mTLS STRICT
No external traffic             Ingress Service deleted
Pods can't talk                 No sidecar injection
Traffic blackhole               DestinationRule mismatch


====================================================================
12. PRODUCTION SMOKE TESTS
====================================================================

From inside cluster:
kubectl run tmp --rm -it --image=curlimages/curl -- sh
curl http://service-name.namespace

From outside:
curl -v https://your-domain


